Problem Statement: Reducing Data Complexity
Imagine you are working with a dataset of Athletic Performance. You have measured several features: Sprint Speed, Long Jump Distance, Vertical Leap, and Leg Strength.

These variables are highly correlated (e.g., fast sprinters usually have high vertical leaps). Handling all four variables is redundant. You want to use Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to compress these features into a single "Athleticism Index" (Principal Component) that captures the maximum variance of the original data.

The Python Implementation
We use PCA from scikit-learn. We will take 2D data (Height and Weight) and reduce it to 1D to visualize the compression.

Expected Output
PCA finds a new axis (the Principal Component) that represents the direction of the greatest spread in the data.

Console Output:

Original Data (First 2 rows): > [[170, 65], [180, 80]]

Reduced Data (First 2 rows): > [[ -2.31], [ 14.82]]

Variance captured by this 1 component: 98.45%

Understanding the Results
Dimensionality Reduction: We started with two numbers (Height, Weight) and ended with one. This single number now represents the "essence" of both original features.

Explained Variance (98.45%): This is a huge win. It means that by using only one variable instead of two, we only lost about 1.5% of the information/patterns in the original dataset.

Feature Combination: PCA doesn't just "pick" Height or Weight; it creates a mathematical combination of both.

Standardization Note: In real-world scenarios, you should always scale your data (using StandardScaler) before PCA, as it is very sensitive to the units of measurement.
